<div class="contents">
<div class="textblock"><h1><a class="anchor" id="intro_sec"></a>
Introduction</h1>
<p>CARMEN code was firstly developed by Olivier Roussel to perform the simulation of the Advection-diffusion, Burgers-diffusion, Flame front, Flame ball, Flame-curl interaction and Navier-Stokes equations with the finite volume method in the context of the adaptive multiresolution analysis for cell-averages. The code was extended to the resistive and ideal MHD equations in order to take advantage of the wavelet based multiresolution algorithm. Its development was done in such a way that the code structure was exclusively for MHD simulations.</p>
<p>The MHD equations are given by</p>
 
<head>
<script type="text/javascript" src="http://latex.codecogs.com/latexit.js"></script>
<script type="text/javascript">
LatexIT.add('p',true);
</script>
</head>
<ul><ul><ul><ul><ul>
<div lang="latex">
  \frac{\partial \rho}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot(\rho\textbf{u})=0,
</div>
<div lang="latex">
  \frac{\partial(\rho\textbf{u})}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left[ \rho\textbf{uu} + \left( p +\frac{\textbf{B}^2}{2}\right)\textbf{I} -\textbf{BB}\right]=0,
</div>
<div lang="latex">
  \frac{\partial \mathcal{E}}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left[ (\mathcal{E}+p)\textbf{u} + \textbf{u}\cdot\left( \frac{\textbf{B}^2}{2}\textbf{I} - \textbf{BB} \right) \right]=\nabla\cdot\left[\textbf{B}\times\eta(\nabla\times\textbf{B})\right],
  </div>
<div lang="latex">
\frac{\partial\textbf{B}}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left(\textbf{uB}-\textbf{Bu}\right)=-\nabla\times(\eta\nabla\times\textbf{B})
</div>
</ul></ul></ul></ul></ul>
<p>where $\rho$ is the density, $\textbf{u}$ the fluid velocity, $\textbf{B}$ the magnetic field, $\eta$ the resistivity, and $\textbf{I}$ the $3\times 3$ identity matrix. </p>
<p> The energy density $\mathcal{E}$ is given by </p>
<ul><ul><ul><ul><ul>
<div lang="latex">
  \mathcal{E}= \frac{p}{\gamma-1} + \frac{\rho\textbf{u}}{2} + \frac{\textbf{B}}{2},
</div>
</ul></ul></ul></ul></ul>
<p> where $p$ is the pressure and $\gamma$ the adiabatic constant. </p>
